{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9d3ba417-578e-4fa5-a33c-465ade859bfa","content":"Here's the correct skip attribute for each framework:\n\n| Framework | Attribute | Example |\n|-----------|-----------|---------|\n| **MSTest** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` | `[Ignore(\"Blocked by bug #123\")]` |\n| **xUnit** | `[Fact(Skip = \"reason\")]` | `[Fact(Skip = \"Blocked by bug #123\")]` |\n| **NUnit** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` | `[Ignore(\"Blocked by bug #123\")]` |\n| **TUnit** | `[Skip(\"reason\")]` | `[Skip(\"Blocked by bug #123\")]` |\n\n**Notes:**\n- **xUnit** `[Theory]` also supports `Skip`: `[Theory(Skip = \"reason\")]`\n- **MSTest/NUnit** `[Ignore]` goes alongside `[TestMethod]`/`[Test]`, not inside it.\n- All four frameworks will report skipped tests in `dotnet test` output so they stay visible.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"25608b3e-6043-414c-859f-3298e730ff1d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the correct skip/ignore attributes for each test framework. Let me provide a concise answer from my knowledge.","outputTokens":279,"requestId":"9C42:1554C1:16A1A49:19493C5:69F86328"},"id":"b1c34506-aa24-4494-b741-7d6679127032","timestamp":"2026-05-04T09:13:19.858Z","parentId":"413961aa-21d3-464a-be90-d46dc80fae92"}
